<p>The <b>SVD</b> (=D0=A1=D0=92=D0=94; <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Russian_language" title=3D"Russian language">Russian</a>: <span lang=
=3D"ru">=D1=81=D0=BD=D0=B0=D0=B9=D0=BF=D0=B5=D1=80=D1=81=D0=BA=D0=B0=D1=8F =
=D0=B2=D0=B8=D0=BD=D1=82=D0=BE=D0=B2=D0=BA=D0=B0 =D0=94=D1=80=D0=B0=D0=B3=
=D1=83=D0=BD=D0=BE=D0=B2=D0=B0</span>, <small><a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Romanization_of_Russian" title=3D"Romanization of Russian">roma=
nized</a>:&nbsp;</small><span title=3D"Russian-language romanization"><i la=
ng=3D"ru-Latn">snayperskaya vintovka Dragunova</i></span>, <small><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Literal_translation" title=3D"Literal tra=
nslation">lit.</a>=E2=80=89</small><span class=3D"gloss-quot">'</span><span=
 class=3D"gloss-text">Dragunov sniper rifle</span><span class=3D"gloss-quot=
">'</span>), <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/GRAU" class=3D"mw-red=
irect" title=3D"GRAU">GRAU</a> index <b>6V1</b>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-2" clas=
s=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SVD_(rifle)#cite_n=
ote-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]=
</span></a></sup> is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Semi-automa=
tic_rifle" title=3D"Semi-automatic rifle">semi-automatic</a> <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Designated_marksman_rifle" title=3D"Designated m=
arksman rifle">designated marksman rifle</a>/<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Sniper_rifle" title=3D"Sniper rifle">sniper rifle</a><sup id=3D"=
cite_ref-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SV=
D_(rifle)#cite_note-3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>3<span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Chamber_(firearms)" title=3D"Chamber (firearms)">chambered</a> in the 7.62=
=C3=9754mmR cartridge, developed in the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Soviet_Union" title=3D"Soviet Union">Soviet Union</a>.
</p>
<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc">
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"History">History</h2><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSVD_(rifle)&amp;action=
=3Dedit&amp;section=3D1" title=3D"Edit section: History"><span>edit</span><=
/a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The SVD was designed to serve in a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Squad" title=3D"Squad">squad</a> support role to provide precise long-r=
ange engagement capabilities to ordinary troops following the <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Warsaw_Pact" title=3D"Warsaw Pact">Warsaw Pact<=
/a> adoption of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/7.62%C3%9739mm=
" title=3D"7.62=C3=9739mm">7.62=C3=9739mm</a> <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Intermediate_cartridge" title=3D"Intermediate cartridge">interm=
ediate cartridge</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Assault_r=
ifle" title=3D"Assault rifle">assault rifles</a> as standard infantry weapo=
n systems. At the time, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NATO" titl=
e=3D"NATO">NATO</a> used <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Battle_ri=
fle#Cold_War" title=3D"Battle rifle">battle rifles</a> chambered for the <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/7.62%C3%9751mm_NATO" title=3D"7.62=
=C3=9751mm NATO">7.62=C3=9751mm NATO</a> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Fully_powered_cartridge" title=3D"Fully powered cartridge">fully pow=
ered cartridge</a> as standard infantry weapon systems and had not yet adop=
ted an intermediate cartridge and assault rifle of their own, allowing them=
 to outrange their Warsaw Pact counterparts.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-krtraining1=
_4-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SVD_(rif=
le)#cite_note-krtraining1-4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The SVD was developed through 1958=E2=80=931963 and selected as the =
winner of a contest that included three competing groups of designers, led =
by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sergei_Gavrilovich_Simonov" cla=
ss=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Sergei Gavrilovich Simonov">Sergei Simonov</a> =
(prototype rejected in April 1960), Aleksandr Konstantinov, and <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yevgeny_Dragunov" title=3D"Yevgeny Dragunov">=
Yevgeny Dragunov</a>. Extensive field testing of the rifles conducted in a =
wide range of environmental conditions (Konstantinov's competing 2B-W-10 pr=
ototype was simpler and cheaper but tested less accurate, durable and relia=
ble) resulted in Dragunov's proposal chambered for the 7.62=C3=9754mmR full=
y powered cartridge being accepted into service in July 1963.<sup id=3D"cit=
e_ref-milmag.pl_5-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/SVD_(rifle)#cite_note-milmag.pl-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</s=
pan>5<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> An initial pre-product=
ion batch consisting of 200 rifles was assembled for evaluation purposes, a=
nd from 1964 serial production was carried out by Izhmash, later called <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kalashnikov_Concern" title=3D"Kalashn=
ikov Concern">Kalashnikov Concern</a>.
</p>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-left" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Chukavin_SVCH_sniper_rifle_in_=
Russian_pavilion_at_Dubai_Airshow_2023.jpg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><=
img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e2/Chukav=
in_SVCH_sniper_rifle_in_Russian_pavilion_at_Dubai_Airshow_2023.jpg/250px-Ch=
ukavin_SVCH_sniper_rifle_in_Russian_pavilion_at_Dubai_Airshow_2023.jpg" dec=
oding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"188" class=3D"mw-file-element" data=
-file-width=3D"1600" data-file-height=3D"1200"></a><figcaption>The Chukavin=
 SVCh is intended to replace the SVD in Russian service</figcaption></figur=
e>
<p>Since then, the SVD has become the standard squad support weapon of seve=
ral countries, including those of the former Warsaw Pact. China produced a =
copy of the SVD through <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Reverse-en=
gineered" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Reverse-engineered">reverse-engine=
ered</a> samples captured during the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Sino-Vietnamese_War" title=3D"Sino-Vietnamese War">Sino-Vietnamese War</=
a> as the Type 79 and 85.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-6" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SVD_(rifle)#cite_note-6"><span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">[</span>6<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Iran =
also produced a clone, the Nakhjir 3, which was a direct copy of the Chines=
e Type 79.
</p><p>In Russian service, the SVD is to be replaced with the <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chukavin_sniper_rifle" title=3D"Chukavin sniper=
 rifle">Chukavin SVCh</a> sniper/designated marksman rifle. In February 202=
3, it was reported that the Chukavin SVCh began to be mass-produced by <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kalashnikov_Concern" title=3D"Kalashni=
kov Concern">Kalashnikov Concern</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-7" class=3D"refere=
nce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SVD_(rifle)#cite_note-7"><spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a>=
</sup> When chambered for the 7.62=C3=9754mmR, the Chukavin SVCh uses SVD c=
ompatible box magazines.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-8" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SVD_(rifle)#cite_note-8"><span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">[</span>8<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup i=
d=3D"cite_ref-9" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/SVD_(rifle)#cite_note-9"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>9<span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-10" class=3D"refe=
rence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SVD_(rifle)#cite_note-10"><=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>10<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span>=
</a></sup>
</p><p>In Ukrainian service, the SVD was largely replaced in the sniping ro=
le with Western sniper rifles chambered in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/.338_Lapua_Magnum" title=3D".338 Lapua Magnum">.338 Lapua Magnum</=
a> or 7.62=C3=9751mm NATO cartridges and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Anti-materiel_rifle" title=3D"Anti-materiel rifle">anti-materiel rif=
les</a> such as the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Barrett_M107A1=
" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Barrett M107A1">Barrett M107A1</a>.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMcNab202371_11-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SVD_(rifle)#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMcNab202371-11"><spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>11<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-12" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/SVD_(rifle)#cite_note-12"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</=
span>12<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The domestically pro=
duced <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/UAR-10" class=3D"mw-redirect=
" title=3D"UAR-10">UAR-10</a> sniper rifle is also replacing the SVD in Ukr=
ainian military and law enforcement units.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMcNab=
202371=E2=88=9272_13-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/SVD_(rifle)#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMcNab202371%E2%88%9272-13"><span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>13<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></s=
up> According to McNab, the SVD remains in service with Ukrainian forces in=
 the designated marksman rifle role.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMcNab202372=
_14-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SVD_(ri=
fle)#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMcNab202372-14"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span=
>14<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Design">Design</h2><span cl=
ass=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSVD_(rifle)&amp;action=
=3Dedit&amp;section=3D2" title=3D"Edit section: Design"><span>edit</span></=
a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The SVD bears a number of cosmetic similarities to the <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kalashnikov_rifle" title=3D"Kalashnikov rifle">AK</=
a> family of rifles but these similarities are for the purpose of standardi=
zing manual of arms. This has occasionally led to misidentification of the =
SVD as an AK variant, and vice versa.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Operating_mechanism">Operat=
ing mechanism</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsect=
ion-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=
=3DSVD_(rifle)&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D3" title=3D"Edit section: Op=
erating mechanism"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-brack=
et">]</span></span></div>
<p>The barrel breech is locked through a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Rotating_bolt" title=3D"Rotating bolt">rotating bolt</a> (left rotat=
ion) and uses three locking lugs to engage corresponding locking recesses i=
n the barrel extension. The rifle has a hammer-type striking mechanism and =
a manual lever safety selector. In addition to the trigger disconnect, the =
fire control mechanism has a second disconnector which does not allow the h=
ammer to fall until the bolt has been closed, similar to a <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sear_(firearm)" title=3D"Sear (firearm)">sear</a> =
in a select-fire weapon. However, the SVD was only designed for semi-automa=
tic fire. The firing pin in the SVD is not retained, i.e. "free-floating", =
and it is therefore possible for accidental discharge to occur as the bolt =
pushes an unfired cartridge into the chamber, should there be an obstructio=
n in the firing pin channel resulting from poor maintenance or extreme cold=
.
</p><p>The firearm is operated by a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Gas-operated_reloading" title=3D"Gas-operated reloading">short-stroke gas=
 piston</a> system with a two-position gas regulator. The gas regulator can=
 be set with the help of the rim of a cartridge. Position #1 leaves a gas e=
scape port opened, whereas position #2 closes the gas escape port and direc=
ts extra gas to the piston, increasing the recoil velocity of the gas-pisto=
n system and is used for resolving reliability issues, which arise from fou=
ling in the gas port/action, extreme cold, high altitude, or using under-po=
wered ammunition.
</p><p>The rifle is fed from a detachable curved <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Magazine_(firearms)#Box" title=3D"Magazine (firearms)">box m=
agazine</a> with a 10-round capacity and the cartridges are double-stacked =
in a staggered zigzag pattern. After discharging the last cartridge from th=
e magazine, the bolt carrier and bolt are held back on a bolt catch that is=
 released by pulling the cocking handle to the rear.
</p><p>The rifle's <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Receiver_(firea=
rms)" title=3D"Receiver (firearms)">receiver</a> is <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Machining" title=3D"Machining">machined</a> to improve pr=
ecision by adding <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Torsion_(mechani=
cs)" title=3D"Torsion (mechanics)">torsional</a> strength.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Barrel">Barrel</h3><span cl=
ass=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSVD_(rifle)&amp;action=
=3Dedit&amp;section=3D4" title=3D"Edit section: Barrel"><span>edit</span></=
a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gun_barrel" title=3D"Gun ba=
rrel">barrel</a> profile is relatively thin to save weight. Its bore is <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chromium" title=3D"Chromium">chrome</=
a>-lined for increased corrosion resistance and features four right-hand gr=
ooves. Originally, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Twist_rate"=
 class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Twist rate">twist rate</a> was 320&nbsp;mm =
(1:12.6 in), as it had been designed for use with heavier civilian ammuniti=
on. In 1975 the twist rate was increased to the standard 240&nbsp;mm (1:9.4=
 in), which reduced the precision with the 7N1 sniper cartridge by 19% but =
allowed for the use of standard "light" ball steel core LPS Gzh (57-N-323S)=
, as well as its variations (incendiary, tracer, armour-piercing) with acce=
ptable precision.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-15" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SVD_(rifle)#cite_note-15"><span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">[</span>15<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The front =
part of the barrel features the front <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Iron_sights" title=3D"Iron sights">sight</a> assembly and a <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayonet" title=3D"Bayonet">bayonet</a> lug. T=
he muzzle is equipped with a permanently affixed long-slotted <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flash_hider" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Fla=
sh hider">flash hider</a>.
</p><p>In order to pass inspections at the factory, these rifles must not p=
roduce more than a 0.7 MOA median deviation from the expected point of impa=
ct in three 10-shot groups using 7N1 (approximately 3 MOA).
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Ammunition">Ammunition</h3>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</sp=
an><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSVD_(rifle)&amp;=
action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D5" title=3D"Edit section: Ammunition"><span>edi=
t</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>To enable the SVD's desired precision, new 7.62=C3=9754mmR "sniper" ammu=
nition, designated 7N1, was designed by V. M. Sabelnikov, P. P. Sazonov and=
 V. M. Dvorianinov in 1966 to meet the new standards. 7N1 sniper cartridges=
 should not produce more than 1.24 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Minute_of_arc" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Minute of arc">MOA</a> extre=
me vertical spread with 240&nbsp;mm twist rate barrels and no more than 1.0=
4 MOA extreme vertical spread with 320&nbsp;mm twist rate barrels in a 5-sh=
ot group. The precision requirements demanded of the SVD with 7N1 is simila=
r to the American <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/M24_Sniper_Weapo=
n_System" title=3D"M24 Sniper Weapon System">M24 Sniper Weapon System</a> w=
ith M118SB cartridges (1.18 MOA extreme vertical spread) and the <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/M110_Semi-Automatic_Sniper_System" title=3D"=
M110 Semi-Automatic Sniper System">M110 Semi-Automatic Sniper System</a> wi=
th M118LR ammunition (1.27 MOA extreme vertical spread).
</p><p>7N1 differed from the standard LPS Gzh (57-N-323S) cartridge in its =
use of finely extruded propellant and a modified projectile containing a vo=
id inside of the jacket at the tip which improved terminal ballistics and a=
 bimetal lead and mild steel core. With standard 57-N-323S cartridges, the =
precision of the SVD is reduced to 2.21 MOA extreme vertical spread. This a=
mmunition was later replaced by 7N14 in 1999, which replaced the mild steel=
 penetrator with a hardened steel penetrator in response to the development=
 of infantry body armour.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Sights">Sights</h3><span cl=
ass=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSVD_(rifle)&amp;action=
=3Dedit&amp;section=3D6" title=3D"Edit section: Sights"><span>edit</span></=
a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Pso-1onsvd.jpg" class=3D"mw-file-description"=
><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/55/Pso-=
1onsvd.jpg/250px-Pso-1onsvd.jpg" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D=
"187" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"3188" data-file-height=
=3D"2379"></a><figcaption>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/PSO-=
1" title=3D"PSO-1">PSO-1</a>'s unique reticle. The rangefinder is in the lo=
wer left, chevrons for distances beyond 1,000&nbsp;m (1,094&nbsp;yd) are fo=
und in the middle, and stadia marks for windage are to the left and right o=
f the center reticule. The reticle is illuminated by a small battery-powere=
d lamp.</figcaption></figure>
<p>The rifle features adjustable <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/I=
ron_sight" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Iron sight">iron sights</a> with =
a sliding tangent rear sight, graduated from 100 to 1,200&nbsp;m (109 to 1,=
312&nbsp;yd) in 100&nbsp;m (109&nbsp;yd) increments. The iron sights can be=
 used with or without the standard-issue optical sight in place. This is po=
ssible because the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scope_mount" ti=
tle=3D"Scope mount">scope mount</a> does not block the area between the fro=
nt and rear sights.
</p><p>The SVD was originally issued with a detachable <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/PSO-1" title=3D"PSO-1">PSO-1</a> <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Telescopic_sight" title=3D"Telescopic sight">optical si=
ght</a> (later upgraded and semi-issued as the PSO-1M2), which mounts to a =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Warsaw_Pact_rail" class=3D"mw-redi=
rect" title=3D"Warsaw Pact rail">Warsaw Pact rail</a> on the left side of t=
he receiver.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-arf.com_16-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SVD_(rifle)#cite_note-arf.com-16"><span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>16<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></=
sup> The PSO-1 elevation turret features <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Bullet_drop_compensation" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Bullet drop=
 compensation">bullet drop compensation</a> (BDC) in 50 metres (55&nbsp;yd)=
 or 100 metres (109&nbsp;yd) increments for engaging point and area targets=
 at ranges from 100 metres (109&nbsp;yd) up to 1,000 metres (1,094&nbsp;yd)=
. At longer distances, the shooter must use the chevrons that would shift t=
he trajectory by 100 metres (109&nbsp;yd) per each chevron. The BDC feature=
 must be tuned at the factory for the particular ballistic trajectory of a =
particular combination of rifle and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Cartridge_(weaponry)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Cartridge (weaponry)=
">cartridge</a> at a predefined <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ai=
r_density" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Air density">air density</a>. Wit=
h increasing range, inevitable BDC-induced errors will occur when the envir=
onmental and meteorological circumstances deviate from the predefined circu=
mstances for which the BDC was calibrated. Marksmen can be trained to under=
stand the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/External_ballistics#Forc=
es_acting_on_the_projectile" title=3D"External ballistics">main forces acti=
ng on the projectile</a> and their effect on their particular gun and ammun=
ition, and the effects of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/External=
_ballistics#External_factors" title=3D"External ballistics">external factor=
s</a> at longer ranges to counter these errors. The PSO-1 sight enables are=
a targets to be engaged at ranges upwards of 1,300&nbsp;m (1,422&nbsp;yd); =
effective ranges in combat situations have been stated at between 600 and 1=
,300&nbsp;m (656 and 1,422&nbsp;yd), depending on the nature of the target =
(point or area target) quality of ammunition and skill of the shooter.<sup =
id=3D"cite_ref-un_yugo_17-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/SVD_(rifle)#cite_note-un_yugo-17"><span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">[</span>17<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite=
_ref-18" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SVD_(=
rifle)#cite_note-18"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>18<span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Several military issue alternative telescopic sights with varying le=
vels of magnification and reticles are available for the SVD. Rifles design=
ated <b>SVDN</b> come equipped with a night sight, such as the NSP-3, NSPU,=
 PGN-1, NSPUM or the Polish passive PCS-5. Rifles designated <b>SVDN-1</b> =
can use the passive night sight NSPU-3 (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/1PN51" title=3D"1PN51">1PN51</a>)<sup id=3D"cite_ref-19" class=3D"ref=
erence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SVD_(rifle)#cite_note-19">=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>19<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span=
></a></sup> and rifles designated <b>SVDN2</b> can use the passive night si=
ght NSPUM (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1PN58" title=3D"1PN58">=
1PN58</a>).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-20" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/SVD_(rifle)#cite_note-20"><span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>[</span>20<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Commercial non military issue mounts that attach to the Warsaw Pact =
rail mount can allow use of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Picati=
nny_rail" title=3D"Picatinny rail">Picatinny rail</a>-mounted optics.<sup i=
d=3D"cite_ref-21" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/SVD_(rifle)#cite_note-21"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>21<span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Stock">Stock</h3><span clas=
s=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSVD_(rifle)&amp;action=3De=
dit&amp;section=3D7" title=3D"Edit section: Stock"><span>edit</span></a><sp=
an class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The original SVD had a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Birch" t=
itle=3D"Birch">birch</a> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Plywood" =
title=3D"Plywood">plywood</a> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lami=
nates" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Laminates">laminate</a> two-piece han=
dguard/gas tube cover and a skeletonized thumbhole stock equipped with a de=
tachable cheek rest; the latter is removed when using iron sights. Beginnin=
g in the 80's, wooden parts were replaced with synthetic parts made of a bl=
ack <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polymer" title=3D"Polymer">pol=
ymer</a> =E2=80=93 the handguard and gas tube cover are more or less identi=
cal in appearance, while the thumbhole stock is of a different shape.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Accessories">Accessories</h=
3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</=
span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSVD_(rifle)&am=
p;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D8" title=3D"Edit section: Accessories"><span>=
edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Tigr_pso_1_med.jpg" class=3D"mw-file-descript=
ion"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8d/=
Tigr_pso_1_med.jpg/250px-Tigr_pso_1_med.jpg" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"25=
0" height=3D"188" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"600" data-fi=
le-height=3D"450"></a><figcaption>Russian PSO-1M2 military issue 4=C3=9724 =
telescopic sight with the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Warsaw_P=
act_rail" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Warsaw Pact rail">Warsaw Pact rail=
</a> mounting system.</figcaption></figure><p>A number of accessories are i=
ssued with the rifle, including a blade-type <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Bayonet" title=3D"Bayonet">bayonet</a> (<a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/AK-47" title=3D"AK-47">AKM</a> clipped point or the <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/AK-74" title=3D"AK-74">AK-74</a> spear p=
oint bayonet), four spare magazines, a leather or nylon sling, magazine pou=
ch, cleaning kit and an accessory/maintenance kit for the telescopic sight.
</p><p>Also included is a cold weather battery case with a "shirt clip", wi=
th a permanently attached cord [approximately 24" long] ending with another=
 battery case cap that has an extension to press against the internal conta=
ct in lieu of the battery to complete the circuit. Placing the external bat=
tery case into the shooters' clothing close to the body keeps it from freez=
ing; using the clip ensures it remains in place.
</p><p>The clamp-style bipod attaches to machined-out reliefs near the fron=
t of the receiver, it literally grabs the two cut out areas and securely mo=
unts with a large round sized head on the clamp bolt able to tightly attach=
 the bipod. The legs are individually adjustable [as opposed to fixed lengt=
h found on many rifles and LMGs] and can be folded and stowed in a forward =
position negating the need to remove the bipod before placing the rifle int=
o the canvas carrying case. The two legs are held close together with a J-s=
haped clamp attached to one leg and swung over the other leg. Original Sovi=
et/Russian SVD bipods fetch a very high price when they rarely appear on th=
e market.
</p>
