<p><b>SVDN (6V1N)</b> =E2=80=93 A series of variants of the original SVD wh=
ich were issued with various night vision optics.
</p><p><b>SVDS (6V3)</b> =E2=80=93 Attempts to reduce the length of the rif=
le for use by marines, mechanised infantry, and paratroopers began in 1978 =
by adding a folding buttstock and a separate pistol grip. Initially, pre-ex=
isting stock designs were used (such as the one from the AKS-74), but ergon=
omic problems necessitated the design of a unique folding stock.<sup id=3D"=
cite_ref-22" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/S=
VD_(rifle)#cite_note-22"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>22<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The final design was chosen out of a v=
ariety of prototypes and adopted in 1995, which had a metal stock that fold=
ed to the right as to not be interfered by the optic mount and also had a s=
hortened barrel. The stock included a rubber shoulder pad and cheek riser. =
The barrel was also given a heavier profile, the receiver housing was stren=
gthened, the gas cylinder block was improved and a ported, and a shorter co=
nical flash suppressor was adopted. The <b>SVDSN</b> <b>(6V3N)</b> variants=
, much like the SVDN variants, are simply equipped with various night visio=
n devices. Production continues as of 2025 at a reportedly greatly increase=
d rate.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-23" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/SVD_(rifle)#cite_note-23"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</=
span>23<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p><b>SVD-1990 (SVD-90)</b> =E2=80=93 A variant of the SVD with the sto=
ck and handguard made from black polymers.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-24" class=3D"=
reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SVD_(rifle)#cite_note-2=
4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>24<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</s=
pan></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-25" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SVD_(rifle)#cite_note-25"><span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">[</span>25<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p><b>SVDM</b> =E2=80=93 A modernised variant of the SVDS, which entere=
d service in 2018.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-26" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SVD_(rifle)#cite_note-26"><span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">[</span>26<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Compared =
to its predecessor, the SVDM was notably designed with a thicker (and 550&n=
bsp;mm long) barrel, new furniture, and a picatinny rail mount on the new, =
hinged, dust cover. The variable power 1P88-4 (1=D0=9F88-4) telescopic sigh=
t is used as the standard day optic. The SVDM rifle can be used with a deta=
chable bipod, and with a quick-detachable suppressor. The iron sight line f=
eatures a simplified rear sight element and a new front sight element locat=
ed above the gas block. The SVDM has a length of 1,135&nbsp;mm (44.7&nbsp;i=
n) (975&nbsp;mm (38.4&nbsp;in) with the stock folded) and weighs 5.3&nbsp;k=
g (12&nbsp;lb).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-27" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SVD_(rifle)#cite_note-27"><span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">[</span>27<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p><b><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dragunov_SVU" title=3D"D=
ragunov SVU">OTs-03 SVU</a></b> =E2=80=93 A variant of the TKB-0172 which b=
egan serial production in 1991 for the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Russian_Ministry_of_Internal_Affairs" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"R=
ussian Ministry of Internal Affairs">MVD</a>. The rifle was also equipped w=
ith an improved <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Muzzle_brake" titl=
e=3D"Muzzle brake">muzzle brake</a> as well as a rear aperture sight, much =
like the original SVD prototype. Many were not new production rifles, but i=
nstead, retrofitted SVDs. A select-fire variant <b>(OTs-03A(S) SVU-A)</b> w=
as also produced in small quantities to serve as an automatic rifle, but th=
e automatic fire capability was later removed from the design. The original=
 shortened barrel was also later replaced with a full-length barrel in the =
design.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Prototypes">Prototypes</h3>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</sp=
an><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSVD_(rifle)&amp;=
action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D10" title=3D"Edit section: Prototypes"><span>ed=
it</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Dragunovedit.png" class=3D"mw=
-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commo=
ns/thumb/4/41/Dragunovedit.png/250px-Dragunovedit.png" decoding=3D"async" w=
idth=3D"250" height=3D"119" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"62=
0" data-file-height=3D"296"></a><figcaption>Pair of Dragunovs imported to t=
he U.S. as Tigers. The top rifle has a cheek pad, two 10-round magazines, a=
nd a flash suppressor. The bottom rifle was marketed as a hunting "carbine"=
. It has no cheek pad, two 5-round magazines, and no flash suppressor.</fig=
caption></figure>
<p><b>SSV-58</b> =E2=80=93 The prototype submitted to trials by Dragunov. T=
he design lacked the fixed flash hider and bayonet lug, which was added to =
the rifle prior to adoption. The rear sights were mounted to the dust cover=
 and were aperture sights instead of the standard notch sight.
</p><p><b>TKB-0172</b> =E2=80=93 An early bullpup design of the SVD develop=
ed by the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/KBP_Instrument_Design_Bu=
reau" title=3D"KBP Instrument Design Bureau">Tula Sporting and Hunting Weap=
ons Design Bureau</a> in the 80's. This rifle also had a significantly shor=
tened barrel to reduce length.
</p><p><b>V-70</b> =E2=80=93 A prototype automatic rifle developed in 1968.=
 It involved the development of a new bipod, a thicker and shorter barrel w=
ith a new muzzle device, and 15/20-round magazines. The detachable bipod de=
signed for this project would be used in subsequent models of SVD.
</p><p><b>AF</b> =E2=80=93 A prototype automatic rifle developed in the mid=
 70's. The prototypes were chambered in 5.45=C3=9739mm and made compatible =
with AK-74 magazines (specifically, the 45-round magazine also compatible w=
ith the RPK-74).
</p><p><b>SVDG (6V1-10)</b> =E2=80=93 A smoothbore SVD with a 10&nbsp;mm bo=
re developed alongside the modern intermediate cartridge program to use the=
 experimental 3&nbsp;mm <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Armour-pie=
rcing_fin-stabilized_discarding_sabot" title=3D"Armour-piercing fin-stabili=
zed discarding sabot">APFSDS</a> projectile, originally designed for use in=
 standard machine guns. The design was not implemented due to the projectil=
e's poor terminal ballistics and the complexity of the new weapon.
</p><p><b>SSV-6 (6V1-6)</b> =E2=80=93 Chambered in the experimental 6mm car=
tridge developed in the 80's. The weapon was not adopted due to the cartrid=
ge's poor effectiveness.
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SVDK" title=3D"SVDK"><b>SVD=
K (6V9)</b></a> =E2=80=93 An experimental Russian variant chambered for the=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/9.3%C3%9764mm_Brenneke" title=3D"=
9.3=C3=9764mm Brenneke">9.3=C3=9764mm 7N33</a> cartridge, based on the civi=
lian Tigr-9 design.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Civilian_variants">Civilian=
 variants</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-=
bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSV=
D_(rifle)&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D11" title=3D"Edit section: Civili=
an variants"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]<=
/span></span></div>
<p><b>Tigr</b> =E2=80=93 A civilian variant of the SVD, lacking a bayonet l=
ug, first produced in the 1970s. Serial production for began in 1992<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-28" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/SVD_(rifle)#cite_note-28"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>28<span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> For export into the United States,=
 the sear which prevented out-of-battery discharge had to be removed to com=
ply with the National Firearms Act. Tiger rifles were available with shorte=
ned (520&nbsp;mm) and full length (620&nbsp;mm) barrels, different stocks (=
including an SVDS-style folding stock), and are chambered in <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/7.62%C3%9754mmR" title=3D"7.62=C3=9754mmR">7.62=
=C3=9754mmR</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/.308_Winchester" =
title=3D".308 Winchester">.308 Winchester</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/.30-06_Springfield" title=3D".30-06 Springfield">.30-06 Spring=
field</a> or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/9.3%C3%9764mm_Brennek=
e" title=3D"9.3=C3=9764mm Brenneke">9.3=C3=9764mm Brenneke</a>.
</p><p><b>Kalashnikov TG3</b> =E2=80=93 Civilian variant of the SVD from Ka=
lashnikov Concern, chambered in 9.6=C3=9753mm Lancaster, first revealed in =
2018. TG3 rifle weighs 3.9 kilograms (8 lb 9.5 oz). The overall length is 1=
,225&nbsp;mm (48 inches) with a barrel length of 620&nbsp;mm (24.4 inches).=
 The TG3 uses five-round single-stack detachable box magazines. The Tg3 is =
an oval-bore (Lancaster rifling) firearm. Although legally a shotgun, the T=
G3 is designed to offer rifle-like performance, at least at shorter distanc=
es. Russian gun laws restrict rifle ownership for newer gun owners but have=
 far fewer restrictions on shotguns. The TG3 is similar to .366 tkm Ak plat=
form weapons common in the Russian gun market.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Foreign_variants">Foreign v=
ariants</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-br=
acket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSVD_=
(rifle)&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D12" title=3D"Edit section: Foreign =
variants"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</sp=
an></span></div>
<p><b>SWD-M</b> =E2=80=93 A modernised Polish variant of the SVD, which was=
 adopted in 1998 and uses a heavy barrel, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Bipod" title=3D"Bipod">bipod</a> (mounted to the forearm) and LD-6 =
(6=C3=9742) telescopic sight.
</p><p><b>Al-Kadesih</b> =E2=80=93 An Iraqi variant of the SVD, not to be c=
onfused with the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tabuk_Sniper_Rifl=
e" title=3D"Tabuk Sniper Rifle">Tabuk rifle</a>. Although the design is ver=
y similar to the SVD, many parts are not interchangeable due to its unique =
dimensions and design characteristics. For example, the receiver is not mil=
led and is slightly longer than that of the SVD, and the barrel is pinned t=
o the receiver instead of being threaded. The rifle is also issued magazine=
s with an ornamental palm tree relief.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-29" class=3D"refe=
rence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SVD_(rifle)#cite_note-29"><=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>29<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span>=
</a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-30" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/SVD_(rifle)#cite_note-30"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
[</span>30<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p><b>Type 79/85</b> =E2=80=93 A Chinese variant of the SVD. Although t=
he design is nearly identical to the original SVD, some parts are not inter=
changeable, as the dimensions are slightly different from Soviet production=
 rifles. A small quantity were also chambered in .308 Winchester for export=
. Exported rifles are often referred to as the <b>NDM-86</b> or <b>EM-351.<=
/b>
</p><p><b><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/CS/LR19" title=3D"CS/LR1=
9">CS/LR19</a></b> or <b>NSG-85</b> =E2=80=93 A modernised Chinese variant =
of the Type 85 adopted by the PLA in 2014.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Doctrine">Doctrine</h2><spa=
n class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSVD_(rifle)&amp;acti=
